Definition: Two analogies on manipulating items in a kitchen is given in the form "A : B. C : ?". The phrase "A : B" relates item A to its appropriate manipulation B. Your task is to replace the question mark (?) with the appropriate manipulation of item C, following the "A : B" relation. Your answer should be a verb which shows a way to manipulate the given object.

Positive Examples.explanation: The given analogy relates items to how they are manipulated. Jugs can be poured into. Shoes can be untied.
The given analogy relates items to how they are manipulated. Jars can be opened. Boxes can be opened.
Bottles can be poured into, and safes can be unlocked. So, unlock is a correct output here.

Negative Examples.explanation: The given analogy relates items to how they are manipulated. Backpacks can be unzipped. Safes CANNOT be travelled, and so it not the correct answer.

The given analogy relates items to how they are manipulated. Faucets can be turned. Cupboard is not the right answer for bag, as it does not model the same relation, and it instead models containment.
The given analogy relates items to how they are manipulated. Peas can be shelled. Unlock is not the right answer for present, as presents cannot be unlocked.
